# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: traffic-mirroring
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] In computing, **load balancing** is the process of distributing a set of tasks over a set of resources (computing units) with the aim of making their overall processing more efficient.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing can optimize response time and avoid unevenly overloading some compute nodes while other compute nodes are left idle.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is the subject of research in the field of parallel computers.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Two main approaches exist: static algorithms, which do not take into account the state of the different machines, and dynamic algorithms, which are usually more general and more efficient but require exchanges of information between the different computing units, at the risk of a loss of efficiency.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] A load-balancing algorithm always tries to answer a specific problem.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Among other things, the nature of the tasks, the algorithmic complexity, the hardware architecture on which the algorithms will run as well as required error tolerance, must be taken into account.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Therefore compromise must be found to best meet application-specific requirements.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] The efficiency of load balancing algorithms critically depends on the nature of the tasks.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, the more information about the tasks is available at the time of decision making, the greater the potential for optimization.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Perfect knowledge of the execution time of each of the tasks allows to reach an optimal load distribution (see algorithm of prefix sum).
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Unfortunately, this is in fact an idealized case.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Knowing the exact execution time of each task is an extremely rare situation.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] For this reason, there are several techniques to get an idea of the different execution times.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] First of all, when tasks are relatively homogeneous size, it is possible to consider that each of them will require approximately the average execution time.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the execution time is considerably irregular, other techniques may be used.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] One technique is to add some metadata to each task.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Depending on the previous execution time for similar metadata, it is possible to make inferences for a future task based on statistics.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] In some cases, tasks depend on each other.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] These interdependencies can be illustrated by a directed acyclic graph.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Intuitively, some tasks cannot begin until others are completed.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Assuming that the required time for each of the tasks is known in advance, an optimal execution order must lead to the minimization of the total execution time.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] However, this is an NP-hard problem and therefore can be difficult to solve exactly.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] There are algorithms, like job scheduler, that calculate optimal task distributions using metaheuristic methods.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Another feature of the tasks critical for the design of a load balancing algorithm is their ability to be broken down into subtasks during execution.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] The *tree-shaped computation* algorithm presented later takes great advantage of this specificity.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] A load balancing algorithm is "static" when it does not take into account the state of the system for the distribution of tasks.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Thereby, the system state includes measures such as the load level (and sometimes even overload) of certain processors.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Instead, assumptions about the overall system are made beforehand, such as the arrival times and resource requirements of incoming tasks.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] In addition, the number of processors, their respective power and communication speeds are known.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, static load balancing aims to associate a known set of tasks with the available processors in order to minimize a certain performance function.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] The key design choice is the performance function.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Static load balancing techniques are commonly centralized around a router, or master, which distributes the loads and optimizes the performance function.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] This minimization can take into account information related to the tasks to be distributed, and derive an expected execution time.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] The advantage of static algorithms is that they are easy to set up and can efficient in the case of fairly regular tasks (such as processing HTTP requests from a website).
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] However, there is still some statistical variance in the assignment of tasks which can lead to the overloading of some computing units.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Unlike static load distribution algorithms, dynamic algorithms take into account the current load of each of the computing units (also called nodes) in the system.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] In this approach, tasks can be moved dynamically from an overloaded node to an underloaded node in order to receive faster processing.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] While these algorithms are much more complicated to design, they can improve performance, in particular, when the execution time varies greatly from one task to another.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic load balancing architecture can be more modular since it is not mandatory to have a specific node dedicated to the distribution of work.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] When tasks are uniquely assigned to a processor according to their state at a given moment, it is a unique assignment.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the tasks can be permanently redistributed according to the state of the system and its evolution, this is called dynamic assignment.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] A load balancing algorithm that requires too much communication in order to reach its decisions runs the risk of slowing down the resolution of the overall problem.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Parallel computing infrastructures are often composed of units of different computing power, which should be taken into account for the load distribution.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] For example, lower-powered units may receive requests that require a smaller amount of computation, or, in the case of homogeneous or unknown request sizes, receive fewer requests than larger units.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] For shared-memory computers, managing write conflicts greatly slows down the speed of individual execution of each computing unit.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] However, they can work perfectly well in parallel.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Conversely, in the case of message exchange, each of the processors can work at full speed.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] On the other hand, when it comes to collective message exchange, all processors are forced to wait for the slowest processors to start the communication phase.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] In reality, few systems fall into exactly one of the categories.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] In general, the processors each have an internal memory to store the data needed for the next calculations and are organized in successive clusters.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Often, these processing elements are then coordinated through distributed memory and message passing.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, the load balancing algorithm should be uniquely adapted to a parallel architecture.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Otherwise, there is a risk that the efficiency of parallel problem solving will be greatly reduced.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Adapting to the hardware structures seen above, there are two main categories of load balancing algorithms.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] On the one hand, the one where tasks are assigned by “master” and executed by “workers” who keep the master informed of the progress of their work, and the master can then take charge of assigning or reassigning the workload in case of the dynamic algorithm.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] The literature refers to this as master-worker architecture.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] On the other hand, the control can be distributed between the different nodes.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] The load balancing algorithm is then executed on each of them and the responsibility for assigning tasks (as well as re-assigning and splitting as appropriate) is shared.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] The last category assumes a dynamic load balancing algorithm.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Since the design of each load balancing algorithm is unique, the previous distinction must be qualified.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Thus, it is also possible to have an intermediate strategy, with, for example, "master" nodes for each sub-cluster, which are themselves subject to a global "master".
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] There are also multi-level organizations, with an alternation between master-slave and distributed control strategies.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] The latter strategies quickly become complex and are rarely encountered.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Designers prefer algorithms that are easier to control.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] In the context of algorithms that run over the very long term (servers, cloud...), the computer architecture evolves over time.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] However, it is preferable not to have to design a new algorithm each time.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] One parameter of a load balancing algorithm is therefore its ability to adapt to scalable hardware architecture.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] This is called the scalability of the algorithm.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] An algorithm is called scalable for an input parameter when its performance remains relatively independent of the size of that parameter.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] When the algorithm is capable of adapting to a varying number of computing units, but the number of computing units must be fixed before execution, it is called moldable.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the algorithm is capable of dealing with a fluctuating amount of processors during its execution, the algorithm is said to be malleable.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Most load balancing algorithms are at least moldable.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Especially in large-scale computing clusters, it is not tolerable to execute a parallel algorithm that cannot withstand the failure of one single component.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, fault tolerant algorithms are being developed which can detect outages of processors and recover the computation.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] If the tasks are independent of each other, and if their respective execution time and the tasks can be subdivided, an optimal optimal algorithm is available under these assumptions.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] By dividing the tasks in such a way as to give the same amount of computation to each processor, all that remains to be done is to group the results together.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Using a prefix sum algorithm, this division can be calculated in logarithmic time with respect to the number of processors.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Most of the time, the execution time of a task is unknown and only rough approximations are available.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] This algorithm may be efficient under these assumptions, but is less applicable when task durations are unknown.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Even if the execution time is not known in advance at all, static load distribution is always possible.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] In a round-robin algorithm, the first request is sent to the first server, then the next to the second, and so on down to the last.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Then it is started again, assigning the next request to the first server, and so on.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] This algorithm can be weighted such that the most powerful units receive the largest number of requests and receive them first.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Randomized static load balancing is simply a matter of randomly assigning tasks to the different servers.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the number of tasks is known in advance, it is even more efficient to calculate a random permutation in advance.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] This avoids communication costs for each assignment.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] There is no longer a need for a distribution master because every processor knows what task is assigned to it.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Even if the number of tasks is unknown, it is still possible to avoid communication with a pseudo-random assignment generation known to all processors.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] The performance of this strategy (measured in total execution time for a given fixed set of tasks) decreases with the maximum size of the tasks.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Master-worker schemes are among the simplest dynamic load balancing algorithms.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] A master distributes the workload to all workers (also sometimes referred to as "slaves").
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Initially, all workers are idle and report this to the master.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] The master answers worker requests and distributes the tasks to them.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] When he has no more tasks to give, he informs the workers so that they stop asking for tasks.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] This scheme can distribute work evenly when assignment overhead is low.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Without taking into account the time needed for the assignment, the execution time would be comparable to the prefix sum seen above.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] The problem with this algorithm is that it has difficulty adapting to a large number of processors because of the high amount of necessary communications.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] This lack of scalability makes it quickly inoperable in very large servers or very large parallel computers.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] However, the quality of the algorithm can be greatly improved by replacing the master with a task list that can be used by different processors.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Although this algorithm can be said to be slightly more difficult to implement, it can improve scalability, although still insufficient for very large computing centers.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Another technique to overcome scalability problems when the time needed for task completion is unknown is work stealing.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] The approach consists of assigning to each processor a certain number of tasks in a random or predefined manner, then allowing inactive processors to "steal" work from active or overloaded processors.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Several implementations of this concept exist, defined by a task division model and by the rules determining the exchange between processors.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] While this technique can be particularly effective, it is difficult to implement because it is necessary to ensure that communication does not become the primary occupation of the processors instead of solving the problem.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] In the case of atomic tasks, two main strategies can be distinguished, those where the processors with low load offer their computing capacity to those with the highest load, and those were the most loaded units wish to lighten the workload assigned to them.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] It has been shown that when the network is heavily loaded, it is more efficient for the least loaded units to offer their availability and when the network is lightly loaded, it is the overloaded processors that require support from the most inactive ones.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] This rule of thumb limits the number of exchanged messages.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] In the case where one starts from a single large task that cannot be divided beyond an atomic level, a "Tree-Shaped computation" algorithm can be used, where the parent task is distributed in a work tree.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Initially, many processors have an empty task, except one that works sequentially on it.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Idle processors issue requests randomly to other processors (not necessarily active).
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] If the latter is able to subdivide the task it is working on, it does so by sending part of its work to the node making the request.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] It is then necessary to send a termination signal to the parent processor when the subtask is completed so that it, in turn, sends the message to its parent until it reaches the root of the tree.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] When the first processor, i.e. the root, has finished, a global termination message can be broadcast.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] In the end, it is necessary to assemble the results by going back up the tree.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] The efficiency of such an algorithm is close to the prefix sum when the job cutting and communication time is not too high compared to the work to be done.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] To avoid too high communication costs, it is possible to imagine a list of jobs on shared memory.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, a request is simply reading from a certain position on this shared memory at the request of the master processor.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] In addition to efficient problem solving through parallel computations, load balancing algorithms are widely used in HTTP request management where a site with a large audience must be able to handle a large number of requests per second.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] One of the most commonly used applications of load balancing is to provide a single Internet service from multiple servers, sometimes known as a server farm.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Commonly load-balanced systems include popular web sites, large Internet Relay Chat networks, high-bandwidth File Transfer Protocol (FTP) sites, Network News Transfer Protocol (NNTP) servers, Domain Name System (DNS) servers, and databases.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Round-robin DNS is an alternate method of load balancing that does not require a dedicated software or hardware node.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] In this technique, multiple IP addresses are associated with a single domain name; clients are given IP in a round-robin fashion.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] IP is assigned to clients with a short expiration so the client is more likely to use a different IP the next time they access the Internet service being requested.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Another more effective technique for load-balancing using DNS is to delegate www.example.org as a sub-domain whose zone is served by each of the same servers that are serving the website.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] This technique works particularly well where individual servers are spread geographically on the Internet.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] However, the zone file for www.example.org on each server is different such that each server resolves its own IP Address as the A-record.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] This way, when a server is down, its DNS will not respond and the web service does not receive any traffic.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] If the line to one server is congested, the unreliability of DNS ensures less HTTP traffic reaches that server.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Furthermore, the quickest DNS response to the resolver is nearly always the one from the network's closest server, ensuring geo-sensitive load-balancing .
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] A short TTL on the A-record helps to ensure traffic is quickly diverted when a server goes down.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Consideration must be given to the possibility that this technique may cause individual clients to switch between individual servers in mid-session.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Another approach to load balancing is to deliver a list of server IPs to the client, and then to have the client randomly select the IP from the list on each connection.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] This essentially relies on all clients generating similar loads, and the law of large numbers to achieve a reasonably flat load distribution across servers.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] With this approach, the method of delivery of a list of IPs to the client can vary and may be implemented as a DNS list (delivered to all the clients without any round-robin), or via hardcoding it to the list.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] If a "smart client" is used, detecting that a randomly selected server is down and connecting randomly again, it also provides fault tolerance.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] For Internet services, a server-side load balancer is usually a software program that is listening on the port where external clients connect to access services.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] The load balancer forwards requests to one of the "backend" servers, which usually replies to the load balancer.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] This allows the load balancer to reply to the client without the client ever knowing about the internal separation of functions.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] It also prevents clients from contacting back-end servers directly, which may have security benefits by hiding the structure of the internal network and preventing attacks on the kernel's network stack or unrelated services running on other ports.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Some load balancers provide a mechanism for doing something special in the event that all backend servers are unavailable.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] This might include forwarding to a backup load balancer or displaying a message regarding the outage.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] It is also important that the load balancer itself does not become a single point of failure.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Usually, load balancers are implemented in high-availability pairs which may also replicate session persistence data if required by the specific application.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Certain applications are programmed with immunity to this problem, by offsetting the load balancing point over differential sharing platforms beyond the defined network.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] The sequential algorithms paired to these functions are defined by flexible parameters unique to the specific database.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Numerous scheduling algorithms, also called load-balancing methods, are used by load balancers to determine which back-end server to send a request to.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Simple algorithms include random choice, round robin, or least connections.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] An important issue when operating a load-balanced service is how to handle information that must be kept across the multiple requests in a user's session.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] If this information is stored locally on one backend server, then subsequent requests going to different backend servers would not be able to find it.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] This might be cached information that can be recomputed, in which case load-balancing a request to a different backend server just introduces a performance issue.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Ideally, the cluster of servers behind the load balancer should not be session-aware, so that if a client connects to any backend server at any time the user experience is unaffected.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] This is usually achieved with a shared database or an in-memory session database like Memcached.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] One basic solution to the session data issue is to send all requests in a user session consistently to the same backend server.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] This is known as "persistence" or "stickiness".
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] A significant downside to this technique is its lack of automatic failover: if a backend server goes down, its per-session information becomes inaccessible, and any sessions depending on it are lost.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] The same problem is usually relevant to central database servers; even if web servers are "stateless" and not "sticky", the central database is (see below).
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Assignment to a particular server might be based on a username, client IP address, or random.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Because of changes in the client's perceived address resulting from DHCP, network address translation, and web proxies this method may be unreliable.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Random assignments must be remembered by the load balancer, which creates a burden on storage.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] If the load balancer is replaced or fails, this information may be lost, and assignments may need to be deleted after a timeout period or during periods of high load to avoid exceeding the space available for the assignment table.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] The random assignment method also requires that clients maintain some state, which can be a problem, for example when a web browser has disabled the storage of cookies.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Sophisticated load balancers use multiple persistence techniques to avoid some of the shortcomings of any one method.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Another solution is to keep the per-session data in a database.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] This can reduce performance because it increases the load on the database: the database is best used to store information less transient than per-session data.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] To prevent a database from becoming a single point of failure, and to improve scalability, the database is often replicated across multiple machines, and load balancing is used to spread the query load across those replicas.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Microsoft's ASP.net State Server technology is an example of a session database.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] All servers in a web farm store their session data on State Server and any server in the farm can retrieve the data.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] When the client is a web browser, one approach is to store the per-session data in the browser itself.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] One way to achieve this is to use a browser cookie, suitably time-stamped and encrypted.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Storing session data on the client is generally the preferred solution: then the load balancer is free to pick any backend server to handle a request.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] However, this method of state-data handling may be unsuitable for some complex business logic scenarios, where the session state payload is large and recomputing it with every request on a server is not feasible.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] URL rewriting has major security issues because the end-user can easily alter the submitted URL and thus change session streams.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Yet another solution to storing persistent data is to associate a name with each block of data, and use a distributed hash table to pseudo-randomly assign that name to one of the available servers, and then store that block of data in the assigned server.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Hardware and software load balancers may have a variety of special features.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] The fundamental feature of a load balancer is to be able to distribute incoming requests over a number of backend servers in the cluster according to a scheduling algorithm.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] A ratio can be manually assigned to cause some backend servers to get a greater share of the workload than others.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] This is sometimes used as a simple way to account for some servers having more capacity than others, though it may not always work as desired.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] When the number of available servers drops below a certain number, or the load gets too high, standby servers can be brought online.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] request can become a major part of the demand on the Web Server's CPU; as the demand increases, users will see slower response times, as the TLS overhead is distributed among Web servers.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] To remove this demand on Web servers, a balancer can terminate TLS connections, passing HTTPS requests as HTTP requests to the Web servers.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] If the balancer itself is not overloaded, this does not noticeably degrade the performance perceived by end-users.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] The downside of this approach is that all of the TLS processing is concentrated on a single device (the balancer) which can become a new bottleneck.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Some load balancer appliances include specialized hardware to process TLS.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Instead of upgrading the load balancer, which is quite expensive dedicated hardware, it may be cheaper to forgo TLS offload and add a few web servers.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Also, some server vendors such as Oracle/Sun now incorporate cryptographic acceleration hardware into their CPUs such as the T2000.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] F5 Networks incorporates a dedicated TLS acceleration hardware card in their local traffic manager (LTM) which is used for encrypting and decrypting TLS traffic.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] One clear benefit to TLS offloading in the balancer is that it enables it to do balancing or content switching based on data in the HTTPS request.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] attacks and generally offload work from the servers to a more efficient platform.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] compression available in all modern web browsers.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] The larger the response and the further away the client is, the more this feature can improve response times.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] The trade-off is that this feature puts additional CPU demand on the load balancer and could be done by web servers instead.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Different vendors use different terms for this, but the idea is that normally each HTTP request from each client is a different TCP connection.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] This feature utilises HTTP/1.1 to consolidate multiple HTTP requests from multiple clients into a single TCP socket to the back-end servers.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] The load balancer can buffer responses from the server and spoon-feed the data out to slow clients, allowing the webserver to free a thread for other tasks faster than it would if it had to send the entire request to the client directly.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] An option for asymmetrical load distribution, where request and reply have different network paths.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] The balancer polls servers for application layer health and removes failed servers from the pool.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] The balancer stores static content so that some requests can be handled without contacting the servers.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Some balancers can arbitrarily modify traffic on the way through.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Some balancers can hide HTTP error pages, remove server identification headers from HTTP responses, and encrypt cookies so that end users cannot manipulate them.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] , the ability to give different priorities to different traffic.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Most load balancers can send requests to different servers based on the URL being requested, assuming the request is not encrypted (HTTP) or if it is encrypted (via HTTPS) that the HTTPS request is terminated (decrypted) at the load balancer.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Authenticate users against a variety of authentication sources before allowing them access to a website.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] At least one balancer allows the use of a scripting language to allow custom balancing methods, arbitrary traffic manipulations, and more.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Firewalls can prevent direct connections to backend servers, for network security reasons.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Intrusion prevention systems offer application layer security in addition to the network/transport layer offered by firewall security.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing can be useful in applications with redundant communications links.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] For example, a company may have multiple Internet connections ensuring network access if one of the connections fails.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] A failover arrangement would mean that one link is designated for normal use, while the second link is used only if the primary link fails.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Using load balancing, both links can be in use all the time.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] A device or program monitors the availability of all links and selects the path for sending packets.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] The use of multiple links simultaneously increases the available bandwidth.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] TRILL (Transparent Interconnection of Lots of Links) facilitates an Ethernet to have an arbitrary topology, and enables per flow pair-wise load splitting by way of Dijkstra's algorithm, without configuration and user intervention.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] The catalyst for TRILL was an event at Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center which began on 13 November 2002.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] The concept of Rbridges [sic] was first proposed to the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers in the year 2004, whom in 2005 rejected what came to be known as TRILL, and in the years 2006 through 2012 devised an incompatible variation known as Shortest Path Bridging.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] The IEEE approved the IEEE 802.1aq standard in May 2012, also known as Shortest Path Bridging (SPB).
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] SPB allows all links to be active through multiple equal-cost paths, provides faster convergence times to reduce downtime, and simplifies the use of load balancing in mesh network topologies (partially connected and/or fully connected) by allowing traffic to load share across all paths of a network.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] SPB is designed to reduce configuration errors and preserves the plug-and-play nature that established Ethernet as the de facto protocol at Layer 2.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Many telecommunications companies have multiple routes through their networks or to external networks.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] They use sophisticated load balancing to shift traffic from one path to another to avoid network congestion on any particular link, and sometimes to minimize the cost of transit across external networks or improve network reliability.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Another way of using load balancing is in network monitoring activities.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Load balancers can be used to split huge data flows into several sub-flows and use several network analyzers, each reading a part of the original data.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] This can be used for monitoring fast networks like 10GbE or STM64, where complex processing of the data may not be possible at wire speed.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is widely used in data center networks to distribute traffic across many existing paths between any two servers.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] It allows more efficient use of network bandwidth and reduces provisioning costs.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] In general, load balancing in datacenter networks can be classified as either static or dynamic.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Static load balancing distributes traffic by computing a hash of the source and destination addresses and port numbers of traffic flows and using it to determine how flows are assigned to one of the existing paths.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic load balancing assigns traffic flows to paths by monitoring bandwidth use on different paths.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic assignments can also be proactive or reactive.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] In the former case, the assignment is fixed once made, while in the latter the network logic keeps monitoring available paths and shifts flows across them as network utilization changes (with arrival of new flows or completion of existing ones).
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] A comprehensive overview of load balancing in datacenter networks has been made available.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is often used to implement failover—the continuation of service after the failure of one or more of its components.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] The components are monitored continually (e.g., web servers may be monitored by fetching known pages), and when one becomes unresponsive, the load balancer is informed and no longer sends traffic to it.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] When a component comes back online, the load balancer starts rerouting traffic to it.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] For this to work, there must be at least one component in excess of the service's capacity (N+1 redundancy).
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] This can be much less expensive and more flexible than failover approaches where every single live component is paired with a single backup component that takes over in the event of a failure (dual modular redundancy).
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Some RAID systems can also utilize hot spare for a similar effect.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] This technique can increase fault tolerance by enabling quick substitutions for the most complicated, most failure-prone parts of a system.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] However, it can make the load balancer itself a single point of failure.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] To maintain the necessary high throughput and low latency, organizations commonly deploy load balancing tools capable of advanced TCP optimizations, connection pooling, and adaptive scheduling.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] Such features help distribute incoming data requests evenly across servers or nodes, prevent congestion, and ensure that compute resources remain efficiently utilized.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] When deployed in large-scale or high-performance AI environments, load balancers also mitigate bandwidth constraints and accommodate varying data governance requirements—particularly when sensitive training data cannot be sent to third-party cloud services.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] By routing data locally (on-premises) or across private clouds, load balancers allow AI workflows to avoid public-cloud bandwidth limits, reduce transit costs, and maintain compliance with regulatory standards.
[src:traffic-mirroring/load-balancing-computing] As AI models expand in size (often measured by billions or even trillions of parameters), load balancing for data ingestion has grown in importance for maintaining the reliability, scalability, and cost efficiency of AI factories.
[src:traffic-mirroring/network-traffic-measurement] In computer networks, **network traffic measurement** is the process of measuring the amount and type of traffic on a particular network.
[src:traffic-mirroring/network-traffic-measurement] This is especially important with regard to effective bandwidth management.
[src:traffic-mirroring/network-traffic-measurement] Network performance could be measured using either active or passive techniques.
[src:traffic-mirroring/network-traffic-measurement] Iperf) are more intrusive but are arguably more accurate.
[src:traffic-mirroring/network-traffic-measurement] Passive techniques have less network overhead and hence can run in the background to be used to trigger network management actions.
[src:traffic-mirroring/network-traffic-measurement] A range of studies have been performed from various points on the Internet.
[src:traffic-mirroring/network-traffic-measurement] The AMS-IX (Amsterdam Internet Exchange) is one of the world's largest Internet exchanges.
[src:traffic-mirroring/network-traffic-measurement] It produces a constant supply of simple Internet statistics.
[src:traffic-mirroring/network-traffic-measurement] There are also numerous academic studies that have produced a range of measurement studies on frame size distributions, TCP/UDP ratios and TCP/IP options.
[src:traffic-mirroring/network-traffic-measurement] Various software tools are available to measure network traffic.
[src:traffic-mirroring/network-traffic-measurement] Some tools measure traffic by sniffing and others use SNMP, WMI or other local agents to measure bandwidth use on individual machines and routers.
[src:traffic-mirroring/network-traffic-measurement] However, the latter generally do not detect the type of traffic, nor do they work for machines which are not running the necessary agent software, such as rogue machines on the network, or machines for which no compatible agent is available.
[src:traffic-mirroring/network-traffic-measurement] In the latter case, inline appliances are preferred.
[src:traffic-mirroring/network-traffic-measurement] These would generally 'sit' between the LAN and the LAN's exit point, generally the WAN or Internet router, and all packets leaving and entering the network would go through them.
[src:traffic-mirroring/network-traffic-measurement] In most cases the appliance would operate as a bridge on the network so that it is undetectable by users.
[src:traffic-mirroring/port-mirroring] Network engineers or administrators use port mirroring to analyze and debug data or diagnose errors on a network.
[src:traffic-mirroring/port-mirroring] It helps administrators keep a close eye on network performance and alerts them when problems occur.
[src:traffic-mirroring/port-mirroring] It can be used to mirror either inbound or outbound traffic (or both) on single or multiple interfaces.
[src:traffic-mirroring/reverse-proxy] In computer networks, a **reverse proxy** or surrogate server is a proxy server that appears to any client to be an ordinary web server, but in reality merely acts as an intermediary that forwards the client's requests to one or more ordinary web servers.
[src:traffic-mirroring/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies help increase scalability, performance, resilience, and security, but they also carry a number of risks.
[src:traffic-mirroring/reverse-proxy] Companies that run web servers often set up reverse proxies to facilitate the communication between an Internet user's browser and the web servers.
[src:traffic-mirroring/reverse-proxy] An important advantage of doing so is that the web servers can be hidden behind a firewall on a company-internal network, and only the reverse proxy needs to be directly exposed to the Internet.
[src:traffic-mirroring/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxy servers are implemented in popular open-source web servers.
[src:traffic-mirroring/reverse-proxy] Dedicated reverse proxy servers are used by some of the biggest websites on the Internet.
[src:traffic-mirroring/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy is capable of tracking IP addresses of requests that are relayed through it as well as reading and/or modifying any non-encrypted traffic.
[src:traffic-mirroring/reverse-proxy] However, this implies that anyone who has compromised the server could do so as well.
[src:traffic-mirroring/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies differ from forward proxies, which are used when the client is restricted to a private, internal network and asks a forward proxy to retrieve resources from the public Internet.
[src:traffic-mirroring/reverse-proxy] Large websites and content delivery networks use reverse proxies, together with other techniques, to balance the load between internal servers.
[src:traffic-mirroring/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can keep a cache of static content, which further reduces the load on these internal servers and the internal network.
[src:traffic-mirroring/reverse-proxy] It is also common for reverse proxies to add features such as compression or TLS encryption to the communication channel between the client and the reverse proxy.
[src:traffic-mirroring/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can inspect HTTP headers, which, for example, allows them to present a single IP address to the Internet while relaying requests to different internal servers based on the URL of the HTTP request.
[src:traffic-mirroring/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can hide the existence and characteristics of origin servers.
[src:traffic-mirroring/reverse-proxy] This can make it more difficult to determine the actual location of the origin server / website and, for instance, more challenging to initiate legal action such as takedowns or block access to the website, as the IP address of the website may not be immediately apparent.
[src:traffic-mirroring/reverse-proxy] Additionally, the reverse proxy may be located in a different jurisdiction with different legal requirements, further complicating the takedown process.
[src:traffic-mirroring/reverse-proxy] Application firewall features can protect against common web-based attacks, like a denial-of-service attack (DoS) or distributed denial-of-service attacks (DDoS).
[src:traffic-mirroring/reverse-proxy] Without a reverse proxy, removing malware or initiating takedowns (while simultaneously dealing with the attack) on one's own site, for example, can be difficult.
[src:traffic-mirroring/reverse-proxy] In the case of secure websites, a web server may not perform TLS encryption itself, but instead offload the task to a reverse proxy that may be equipped with TLS acceleration hardware.
[src:traffic-mirroring/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can distribute the load from incoming requests to several servers, with each server supporting its own application area.
[src:traffic-mirroring/reverse-proxy] In the case of reverse proxying web servers, the reverse proxy may have to rewrite the URL in each incoming request in order to match the relevant internal location of the requested resource.
[src:traffic-mirroring/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can reduce load on its origin servers by caching static content and dynamic content, known as web acceleration.
[src:traffic-mirroring/reverse-proxy] Proxy caches of this sort can often satisfy a considerable number of website requests, greatly reducing the load on the origin server(s).
[src:traffic-mirroring/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can optimize content by compressing it in order to speed up loading times.
[src:traffic-mirroring/reverse-proxy] In a technique named "spoon-feeding", a dynamically generated page can be produced in its entirety and served to the reverse proxy, which can feed the page to the client as the connection allows.
[src:traffic-mirroring/reverse-proxy] The program that generates the page need not remain open, thus releasing server resources during the possibly extended time the client requires to complete the transfer.
[src:traffic-mirroring/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can operate wherever multiple web-servers must be accessible via a single public IP address.
[src:traffic-mirroring/reverse-proxy] The web servers listen on different ports in the same machine, with the same local IP address or, possibly, on different machines with different local IP addresses.
[src:traffic-mirroring/reverse-proxy] The reverse proxy analyzes each incoming request and delivers it to the right server within the local area network.
[src:traffic-mirroring/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can perform A/B testing and multivariate testing without requiring application code to handle the logic of which version is served to a client.
[src:traffic-mirroring/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can add access authentication to a web server that does not have any authentication.
[src:traffic-mirroring/reverse-proxy] When the transit traffic is encrypted and the reverse proxy needs to filter/cache/compress or otherwise modify or improve the traffic, the proxy first must decrypt and re-encrypt communications.
[src:traffic-mirroring/reverse-proxy] This requires the proxy to possess the TLS certificate and its corresponding private key, extending the number of systems that can have access to non-encrypted data and making it a more valuable target for attackers.
[src:traffic-mirroring/reverse-proxy] The vast majority of external data breaches happen either when hackers succeed in abusing an existing reverse proxy that was intentionally deployed by an organization, or when hackers succeed in converting an existing Internet-facing server into a reverse proxy server.
[src:traffic-mirroring/reverse-proxy] Compromised or converted systems allow external attackers to specify where they want their attacks proxied to, enabling their access to internal networks and systems.
[src:traffic-mirroring/reverse-proxy] Applications that were developed for the internal use of a company are not typically hardened to public standards and are not necessarily designed to withstand all hacking attempts.
[src:traffic-mirroring/reverse-proxy] When an organization allows external access to such internal applications via a reverse proxy, they might unintentionally increase their own attack surface and invite hackers.
[src:traffic-mirroring/reverse-proxy] If a reverse proxy is not configured to filter attacks or it does not receive daily updates to keep its attack signature database up to date, a zero-day vulnerability can pass through unfiltered, enabling attackers to gain control of the system(s) that are behind the reverse proxy server.
[src:traffic-mirroring/reverse-proxy] Giving the reverse proxy of a third party access to private keys (for caching or optimizing content) places the entire triad of confidentiality, integrity and availability in the hands of the third party who operates the proxy.
[src:traffic-mirroring/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy is a single point of failure for the back-end services it fronts: an outage caused by misconfiguration, a denial-of-service attack, or a software fault can make every fronted service unreachable to outside clients, even when the back-end services themselves remain healthy.
[src:traffic-mirroring/reverse-proxy] For example, a 2020 outage at Cloudflare briefly took down major sites and services that relied on its reverse-proxy edge, including Discord.
[src:traffic-mirroring/service-mesh] In software architecture, a **service mesh** is a dedicated infrastructure layer for facilitating service-to-service communications between services or microservices using a proxy.
[src:traffic-mirroring/service-mesh] A dedicated communication layer can provide numerous benefits, such as providing observability into communications, providing secure connections, and automating retries and backoff for failed requests.
[src:traffic-mirroring/service-mesh] A service mesh consists of network proxies paired with each service in an application and a set of task-management processes.
[src:traffic-mirroring/service-mesh] The proxies are called the data plane and the management processes are called the control plane.
[src:traffic-mirroring/service-mesh] The data plane intercepts calls between different services and processes them; the control plane is the brain of the mesh that coordinates the behavior of proxies and provides APIs for operations and maintenance personnel to manipulate and observe the entire network.
[src:traffic-mirroring/service-mesh] The service mesh architecture is implemented by software products such as Istio, Cilium, Linkerd, Consul, AWS App Mesh, Kuma, Traefik Mesh, and Greymatter.io.
[src:traffic-mirroring/service-mesh] Many service meshes use the Envoy proxy on the data plane.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Software testing can provide objective, independent information about the quality of software and the risk of its failure to a user or sponsor or any other stakeholder.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Software testing can determine the correctness of software for specific scenarios but cannot determine correctness for all scenarios.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Based on the criteria for measuring correctness from an oracle, software testing employs principles and mechanisms that might recognize a problem.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Examples of oracles include specifications, contracts, comparable products, past versions of the same product, inferences about intended or expected purpose, user or customer expectations, relevant standards, and applicable laws.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Software testing can be functional or non-functional in nature.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Software testing is often dynamic in nature: running the software to verify actual output matches expected.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] It can also be static in nature: reviewing code and its associated documentation.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Software testing is often used to answer the question: Does the software do what it is supposed to do and what it needs to do?
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Information learned from software testing may be used to improve the process by which software is developed.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] A commonly suggested approach to automated testing is the "test pyramid," wherein most of the tests are unit tests, followed by a smaller set of integration tests and finally a few end-to-end (e2e) tests.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] A study conducted by NIST in 2002 reported that software bugs cost the U.S. economy $59.5 billion annually.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] More than a third of this cost could be avoided if better software testing was performed.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Outsourcing software testing because of costs is very common, with China, the Philippines, India and Pakistan being preferred destinations.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Myers initially introduced the separation of debugging from testing in 1979.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Although his attention was on breakage testing ("A successful test case is one that detects an as-yet undiscovered error."), it illustrated the desire of the software engineering community to separate fundamental development activities, such as debugging, from that of verification.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Software testing typically includes handling software bugs – a defect in the code that causes an undesirable result.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Bugs generally slow testing progress and involve programmer assistance to debug and fix.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] For example, a defect in dead code will not be considered a failure.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] A defect that does not cause failure at one point in time may lead to failure later due to environmental changes.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Examples of environment change include running on new computer hardware, changes in data, and interacting with different software.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Software testing is typically goal driven.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] A single defect may result in multiple failure symptoms.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Software testing may involve a Requirements gap – omission from the design for a requirement.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Requirement gaps can often be non-functional requirements such as testability, scalability, maintainability, performance, and security.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] A fundamental limitation of software testing is that testing under *all* combinations of inputs and preconditions (initial state) is not feasible, even with a simple product.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Defects that manifest in unusual conditions are difficult to find in testing.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Also, non-functional dimensions of quality (how it is supposed to *be* versus what it is supposed to *do*) – usability, scalability, performance, compatibility, and reliability – can be subjective; something that constitutes sufficient value to one person may not to another.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Although testing for every possible input is not feasible, testing can use combinatorics to maximize coverage while minimizing tests.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Test automation is the use of software (separate from the software being tested) for controlling the execution of tests and comparing actual outcome with predicted.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Test automation supports testing the system under test (SUT) without manual interaction which can lead to faster test execution and testing more often.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Test automation is a key aspect of continuous testing and often for continuous integration and continuous delivery (CI/CD).
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Software testing can be categorized into levels based on how much of the software system is the focus of a test.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Unit testing, a.k.a. component or module testing, is a form of software testing by which isolated source code is tested to validate expected behavior.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Integration testing is a form of software testing in which multiple software components, modules, or services are tested together to verify they work as expected when combined.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] The focus is on testing the interactions and data exchange between integrated parts, rather than testing components in isolation.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] System testing, a.k.a. end-to-end (E2E) testing, is testing conducted on a complete software system.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] There are many approaches to software testing.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Reviews, walkthroughs, or inspections are referred to as static testing, whereas executing programmed code with a given set of test cases is referred to as dynamic testing.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Static testing is often implicit, like proofreading, plus when programming tools/text editors check source code structure or compilers (precompilers) check syntax and data flow as static program analysis.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Dynamic testing takes place when the program itself is run.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Dynamic testing may begin before the program is 100% complete in order to test particular sections of code and are applied to discrete functions or modules.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Typical techniques for these are either using stubs/drivers or execution from a debugger environment.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Static testing involves verification, whereas dynamic testing also involves validation.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Passive testing means verifying the system's behavior without any interaction with the software product.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Contrary to active testing, testers do not provide any test data but look at system logs and traces.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] They mine for patterns and specific behavior in order to make some kind of decisions.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] This is related to offline runtime verification and log analysis.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Exploratory testing is an approach to software testing that is concisely described as simultaneous learning, test design and test execution.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Software testing can often be divided into white-box and black-box.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] These two approaches are used to describe the point of view that the tester takes when designing test cases.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] A hybrid approach called grey-box that includes aspects of both boxes may also be applied to software testing methodology.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] White-box testing (also known as clear box testing, glass box testing, transparent box testing, and structural testing) verifies the internal structures or workings of a program, as opposed to the functionality exposed to the end-user.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] In white-box testing, an internal perspective of the system (the source code), as well as programming skills are used to design test cases.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] The tester chooses inputs to exercise paths through the code and determines the appropriate outputs.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] This is analogous to testing nodes in a circuit, e.g., in-circuit testing (ICT).
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] While white-box testing can be applied at the unit, integration, and system levels of the software testing process, it is usually done at the unit level.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] It can test paths within a unit, paths between units during integration, and between subsystems during a system–level test.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Though this method of test design can uncover many errors or problems, it might not detect unimplemented parts of the specification or missing requirements.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Code coverage tools can evaluate the completeness of a test suite that was created with any method, including black-box testing.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] This allows the software team to examine parts of a system that are rarely tested and ensures that the most important function points have been tested.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] 100% statement coverage ensures that all code paths or branches (in terms of control flow) are executed at least once.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] This is helpful in ensuring correct functionality, but not sufficient since the same code may process different inputs correctly or incorrectly.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Black-box testing (also known as functional testing) describes designing test cases without knowledge of the implementation, without reading the source code.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] The testers are only aware of what the software is supposed to do, not how it does it.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Black-box testing methods include: equivalence partitioning, boundary value analysis, all-pairs testing, state transition tables, decision table testing, fuzz testing, model-based testing, use case testing, exploratory testing, and specification-based testing.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Specification-based testing aims to test the functionality of software according to the applicable requirements.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] This level of testing usually requires thorough test cases to be provided to the tester, who then can simply verify that for a given input, the output value (or behavior), either "is" or "is not" the same as the expected value specified in the test case.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Test cases are built around specifications and requirements, i.e., what the application is supposed to do.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] It uses external descriptions of the software, including specifications, requirements, and designs, to derive test cases.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] These tests can be functional or non-functional, though usually functional.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Specification-based testing may be necessary to assure correct functionality, but it is insufficient to guard against complex or high-risk situations.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Black box testing can be used to any level of testing although usually not at the unit level.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Component interface testing is a variation of black-box testing, with the focus on the data values beyond just the related actions of a subsystem component.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] The practice of component interface testing can be used to check the handling of data passed between various units, or subsystem components, beyond full integration testing between those units.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] The data being passed can be considered as "message packets" and the range or data types can be checked for data generated from one unit and tested for validity before being passed into another unit.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] One option for interface testing is to keep a separate log file of data items being passed, often with a timestamp logged to allow analysis of thousands of cases of data passed between units for days or weeks.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Tests can include checking the handling of some extreme data values while other interface variables are passed as normal values.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Unusual data values in an interface can help explain unexpected performance in the next unit.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] The aim of visual testing is to provide developers with the ability to examine what was happening at the point of software failure by presenting the data in such a way that the developer can easily find the information he or she requires, and the information is expressed clearly.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] At the core of visual testing is the idea that showing someone a problem (or a test failure), rather than just describing it, greatly increases clarity and understanding.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Visual testing, therefore, requires the recording of the entire test process – capturing everything that occurs on the test system in video format.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Output videos are supplemented by real-time tester input via picture-in-a-picture webcam and audio commentary from microphones.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Visual testing provides a number of advantages.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] The quality of communication is increased drastically because testers can show the problem (and the events leading up to it) to the developer as opposed to just describing it, and the need to replicate test failures will cease to exist in many cases.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] The developer will have all the evidence he or she requires of a test failure and can instead focus on the cause of the fault and how it should be fixed.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Ad hoc testing and exploratory testing are important methodologies for checking software integrity because they require less preparation time to implement, while the important bugs can be found quickly.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] In ad hoc testing, where testing takes place in an improvised impromptu way, the ability of the tester(s) to base testing off documented methods and then improvise variations of those tests can result in a more rigorous examination of defect fixes.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] However, unless strict documentation of the procedures is maintained, one of the limits of ad hoc testing is lack of repeatability.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Grey-box testing (American spelling: gray-box testing) involves using knowledge of internal data structures and algorithms for purposes of designing tests while executing those tests at the user, or black-box level.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] The tester will often have access to both "the source code and the executable binary." Grey-box testing may also include reverse engineering (using dynamic code analysis) to determine, for instance, boundary values or error messages.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Manipulating input data and formatting output do not qualify as grey-box, as the input and output are clearly outside of the "black box" that we are calling the system under test.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] This distinction is particularly important when conducting integration testing between two modules of code written by two different developers, where only the interfaces are exposed for the test.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] By knowing the underlying concepts of how the software works, the tester makes better-informed testing choices while testing the software from outside.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Typically, a grey-box tester will be permitted to set up an isolated testing environment with activities, such as seeding a database.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] The tester can observe the state of the product being tested after performing certain actions such as executing SQL statements against the database and then executing queries to ensure that the expected changes have been reflected.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Grey-box testing implements intelligent test scenarios based on limited information.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] This will particularly apply to data type handling, exception handling, and so on.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] With the concept of grey-box testing, this "arbitrary distinction" between black- and white-box testing has faded somewhat.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Installation testing is a type of software testing that verifies that users can successfully install and set up software in its intended environments (e.g., operating systems, computer hardware).
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Most software systems have installation procedures that are needed before they can be used for their main purpose.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Installation testing focuses on these procedures and whether they're sufficient for achieving an installed, usable software system.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Procedures of this kind may involve full or partial upgrades, and install/uninstall processes.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] For example, in the case of a lack of backward compatibility, this can occur because the programmers develop and test software only on the latest version of the target environment, which not all users may be running.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] This results in the unintended consequence that the latest work may not function on earlier versions of the target environment, or on older hardware that earlier versions of the target environment were capable of using.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Sometimes such issues can be fixed by proactively abstracting operating system functionality into a separate program module or library.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Sanity testing determines whether it is reasonable to proceed with further testing.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Smoke testing consists of minimal attempts to operate the software, designed to determine whether there are any basic problems that will prevent it from working at all.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Such tests can be used as build verification test.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Regression testing focuses on finding defects after a major code change has occurred.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Specifically, it seeks to uncover software regressions, as degraded or lost features, including old bugs that have come back.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Such regressions occur whenever software functionality that was previously working correctly, stops working as intended.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Typically, regressions occur as an unintended consequence of program changes, when the newly developed part of the software collides with the previously existing code.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Common methods of regression testing include re-running previous sets of test cases and checking whether previously fixed faults have re-emerged.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] The depth of testing depends on the phase in the release process and the risk of the added features.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] They can either be complete, for changes added late in the release or deemed to be risky, or be very shallow, consisting of positive tests on each feature, if the changes are early in the release or deemed to be of low risk.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Acceptance testing is system-level testing to ensure the software meets customer expectations.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Acceptance testing may be performed at the end or in the middle of a project, including after each completed user story in an agile project.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Tests are frequently grouped into these levels by where they are performed in the software development process, or by the level of specificity of the test.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Sometimes, UAT is performed by the customer, in their environment and on their own hardware.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] OAT is used to conduct operational readiness (prerelease) of a product, service or system as part of a quality management system.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] OAT is a common type of non-functional software testing, used mainly in software development and software maintenance projects.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] This type of testing focuses on the operational readiness of the system to be supported, or to become part of the production environment.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Hence, it is also known as operational readiness testing (ORT) or operations readiness and assurance (OR&A) testing.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Functional testing within OAT is limited to those tests that are required to verify the *non-functional* aspects of the system.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] In addition, the software testing should ensure that the portability of the system, as well as working as expected, does not also damage or partially corrupt its operating environment or cause other processes within that environment to become inoperative.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Contractual acceptance testing is performed based on the contract's acceptance criteria defined during the agreement of the contract, while regulatory acceptance testing is performed based on the relevant regulations to the software product.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Both of these two tests can be performed by users or independent testers.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Regulation acceptance testing sometimes involves the regulatory agencies auditing the test results.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Alpha testing is simulated or actual operational testing by potential users/customers or an independent test team at the developers' site.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Alpha testing is often employed for off-the-shelf software as a form of internal acceptance testing before the software goes to beta testing.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Beta testing comes after alpha testing and can be considered a form of external user acceptance testing.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Versions of the software, known as beta versions, are released to a limited audience outside of the programming team known as beta testers.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] The software is released to groups of people so that further testing can ensure the product has few faults or bugs.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Beta versions can be made available to the open public to increase the feedback field to a maximal number of future users and to deliver value earlier, for an extended or even indefinite period of time (perpetual beta).
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Functional testing refers to activities that verify a specific action or function of the code.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] These are usually found in the code requirements documentation, although some development methodologies work from use cases or user stories.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Non-functional testing refers to aspects of the software that may not be related to a specific function or user action, such as scalability or other performance, behavior under certain constraints, or security.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Testing will determine the breaking point, the point at which extremes of scalability or performance leads to unstable execution.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Non-functional requirements tend to be those that reflect the quality of the product, particularly in the context of the suitability perspective of its users.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Continuous testing is the process of executing automated tests as part of the software delivery pipeline to obtain immediate feedback on the business risks associated with a software release candidate.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Continuous testing includes the validation of both functional requirements and non-functional requirements; the scope of testing extends from validating bottom-up requirements or user stories to assessing the system requirements associated with overarching business goals.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Destructive testing attempts to cause the software or a sub-system to fail.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] It verifies whether the software functions properly when it receives invalid or unexpected inputs, thereby assessing the robustness of input validation and error-management routines.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Software fault injection, in the form of fuzzing, is an example of failure testing.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Various commercial non-functional testing tools are linked from the software fault injection page; there are also numerous open-source and free software tools available that perform destructive testing.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Performance testing is generally executed to determine how a system or sub-system performs in terms of responsiveness and stability under a particular workload.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] It can also serve to investigate, measure, validate or verify other quality attributes of the system, such as scalability, reliability and resource usage.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] There is little agreement on what the specific goals of performance testing are.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] The terms load testing, performance testing, scalability testing, and volume testing, are often used interchangeably.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Real-time software systems have strict timing constraints.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] To test if timing constraints are met, real-time testing is used.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Usability testing is to check if the user interface is easy to use and understand.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] It is concerned mainly with the use of the application.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] This is not a kind of testing that can be automated; actual human users are needed, being monitored by skilled UI designers.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Usability testing can use structured models to check how well an interface works.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] The Stanton, Theofanos, and Joshi (2015) model looks at user experience, and the Al-Sharafat and Qadoumi (2016) model is for expert evaluation, helping to assess usability in digital applications.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Accessibility testing is done to ensure that the software is accessible to persons with disabilities.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Security testing is essential for software that processes confidential data to prevent system intrusion by hackers.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Testing for internationalization and localization validates that the software can be used with different languages and geographic regions.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] The process of pseudolocalization is used to test the ability of an application to be translated to another language, and make it easier to identify when the localization process may introduce new bugs into the product.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Globalization testing verifies that the software is adapted for a new culture, such as different currencies or time zones.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Actual translation to human languages must be tested, too.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Development testing is a software development process that involves the synchronized application of a broad spectrum of defect prevention and detection strategies in order to reduce software development risks, time, and costs.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] It is performed by the software developer or engineer during the construction phase of the software development lifecycle.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Development testing aims to eliminate construction errors before code is promoted to other testing; this strategy is intended to increase the quality of the resulting software as well as the efficiency of the overall development process.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Depending on the organization's expectations for software development, development testing might include static code analysis, data flow analysis, metrics analysis, peer code reviews, unit testing, code coverage analysis, traceability, and other software testing practices.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] A/B testing is a method of running a controlled experiment to determine if a proposed change is more effective than the current approach.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Customers are routed to either a current version (control) of a feature, or to a modified version (treatment) and data is collected to determine which version is better at achieving the desired outcome.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Concurrent or concurrency testing assesses the behaviour and performance of software and systems that use concurrent computing, generally under normal usage conditions.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Typical problems this type of testing will expose are deadlocks, race conditions and problems with shared memory/resource handling.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] In software testing, conformance testing verifies that a product performs according to its specified standards.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Compilers, for instance, are extensively tested to determine whether they meet the recognized standard for that language.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] For example, every output from a serialization function should be accepted by the corresponding deserialization function, and every output from a sort function should be a monotonically increasing list containing exactly the same elements as its input.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Property testing libraries allow the user to control the strategy by which random inputs are constructed, to ensure coverage of degenerate cases, or inputs featuring specific patterns that are needed to fully exercise aspects of the implementation under test.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Property testing is also sometimes known as "generative testing" or "QuickCheck testing" since it was introduced and popularized by the Haskell library QuickCheck.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Metamorphic testing (MT) is a property-based software testing technique, which can be an effective approach for addressing the test oracle problem and test case generation problem.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] The test oracle problem is the difficulty of determining the expected outcomes of selected test cases or to determine whether the actual outputs agree with the expected outcomes.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] VCR testing, also known as "playback testing" or "record/replay" testing, is a testing technique for increasing the reliability and speed of regression tests that involve a component that is slow or unreliable to communicate with, often a third-party API outside of the tester's control.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] It involves making a recording ("cassette") of the system's interactions with the external component, and then replaying the recorded interactions as a substitute for communicating with the external system on subsequent runs of the test.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] The technique was popularized in web development by the Ruby library vcr.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] It is often used in the context of distributed systems, service-oriented software architectures, and microservices.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Since the early 2020s, artificial intelligence has increasingly been integrated into software testing workflows.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] AI-driven testing methods automate the creation of test cases, dynamically adapt to changes, and leverage machine learning to identify high-risk areas of the codebase — an approach that enhances regression testing efficiency while expanding overall test coverage.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] A key development is **self-healing test automation**, in which automated tests automatically detect and adapt to changes in a user interface without human intervention.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Studies of AI-driven test automation across over 3,600 grey literature sources identified self-healing test scripts as one of the most common AI solutions in practice.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] A case study presented at the 2023 International Conference on Information Management and Technology (ICIMTech) found that integrating shift-left testing into an agile development methodology over one year measurably reduced the number of bugs reaching production.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] In an organization, testers may be in a separate team from the rest of the software development team or they may be integrated into one team.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Software testing can also be performed by non-dedicated software testers.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] In the 1980s, the term *software tester* started to be used to denote a separate profession.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Notable software testing roles and titles include: *test manager*, *test lead*, *test analyst*, *test designer*, *tester*, *automation developer*, and *test administrator*.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Organizations that develop software, perform testing differently, but there are common patterns.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] In waterfall development, testing is generally performed after the code is completed, but before the product is shipped to the customer.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] This practice often results in the testing phase being used as a project buffer to compensate for project delays, thereby compromising the time devoted to testing.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Some contend that the waterfall process allows for testing to start when the development project starts and to be a continuous process until the project finishes.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Agile software development commonly involves testing while the code is being written and organizing teams with both programmers and testers and with team members performing both programming and testing.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] One agile practice, test-driven software development (TDD), is a way of unit testing such that unit-level testing is performed while writing the product code.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Test code is updated as new features are added and failure conditions are discovered (bugs fixed).
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Commonly, the unit test code is maintained with the project code, integrated in the build process, and run on each build and as part of regression testing.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Goals of this continuous integration is to support development and reduce defects.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] Even in organizations that separate teams by programming and testing functions, many often have the programmers perform unit testing.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] The sample below is common for waterfall development.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p01] The same activities are commonly found in other development models, but might be described differently.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] The terms verification and validation are commonly used interchangeably in the industry; it is also common to see these two terms defined with contradictory definitions.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] Verification is the process of evaluating a system or component to determine whether the products of a given development phase satisfy the conditions imposed at the start of that phase.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] Validation is the process of evaluating a system or component during or at the end of the development process to determine whether it satisfies specified requirements.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] Verification is confirmation by examination and through provision of objective evidence that specified requirements have been fulfilled.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] Validation is confirmation by examination and through provision of objective evidence that the requirements for a specific intended use or application have been fulfilled.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] The contradiction is caused by the use of the concepts of requirements and specified requirements but with different meanings.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] In the case of IEEE standards, the specified requirements, mentioned in the definition of validation, are the set of problems, needs and wants of the stakeholders that the software must solve and satisfy.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] Such requirements are documented in a Software Requirements Specification (SRS).
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] And, the products mentioned in the definition of verification, are the output artifacts of every phase of the software development process.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] These products are, in fact, specifications such as Architectural Design Specification, Detailed Design Specification, etc.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] The SRS is also a specification, but it cannot be verified (at least not in the sense used here – more on this subject below).
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] But, for the ISO 9000, the specified requirements are the set of specifications, as just mentioned above, that must be verified.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] A specification, as previously explained, is the product of a software development process phase that receives another specification as input.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] A specification is verified successfully when it correctly implements its input specification.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] All the specifications can be verified except the SRS because it is the first one (it can be validated, though).
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] An example scenario be that the Design Specification must implement the SRS, and the Construction phase artifacts must implement the Design Specification.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] So, when these words are defined in common terms, the apparent contradiction disappears.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] Both the SRS and the software must be validated.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] The SRS can be validated statically by consulting with the stakeholders.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] Nevertheless, running some partial implementation of the software or a prototype of any kind (dynamic testing) and obtaining positive feedback from them, can further increase the certainty that the SRS is correctly formulated.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] On the other hand, the software, as a final and running product (not its artifacts and documents, including the source code) must be validated dynamically with the stakeholders by executing the software and having them to try it.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] Some might argue that, for SRS, the input is the words of stakeholders and, therefore, SRS validation is the same as SRS verification.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] Thinking this way is not advisable as it only causes more confusion.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] It is better to think of verification as a process involving a formal and technical input document.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] In some organizations, software testing is part of a software quality assurance (SQA) process.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] In SQA, software process specialists and auditors are concerned with the software development process rather than just the artifacts such as documentation, code and systems.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] They examine and change the software engineering process itself to reduce the number of faults that end up in the delivered software: the so-called defect rate.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] What constitutes an acceptable defect rate depends on the nature of the software; a flight simulator video game would have much higher defect tolerance than software for an actual airplane.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] Although there are close links with SQA, testing departments often exist independently, and there may be no SQA function in some companies.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] Software testing is an activity to investigate software under test in order to provide quality-related information to stakeholders.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] By contrast, QA (quality assurance) is the implementation of policies and procedures intended to prevent defects from reaching customers.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] Quality measures include such topics as correctness, completeness, security and ISO/IEC 9126 requirements such as capability, reliability, efficiency, portability, maintainability, compatibility, and usability.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] There are a number of frequently used software metrics, or measures, which are used to assist in determining the state of the software or the adequacy of the testing.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] A software testing process can produce several artifacts.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] The actual artifacts produced are a factor of the software development model used, stakeholder and organisational needs.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] A test plan is a document detailing the approach that will be taken for intended test activities.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] The plan may include aspects such as objectives, scope, processes and procedures, personnel requirements, and contingency plans.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] The test plan could come in the form of a single plan that includes all test types (like an acceptance or system test plan) and planning considerations, or it may be issued as a master test plan that provides an overview of more than one detailed test plan (a plan of a plan).
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] A test plan can be, in some cases, part of a wide "test strategy" which documents overall testing approaches, which may itself be a master test plan or even a separate artifact.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] In software development, a traceability matrix (TM) is a document, usually in the form of a table, used to assist in determining the completeness of a relationship by correlating any two baselined documents using a many-to-many relationship comparison.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] It is often used with high-level requirements (these often consist of marketing requirements) and detailed requirements of the product to the matching parts of high-level design, detailed design, test plan, and test cases.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] A test case normally consists of a unique identifier, requirement references from a design specification, preconditions, events, a series of steps (also known as actions) to follow, input, output, expected result, and the actual result.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] Clinically defined, a test case is an input and an expected result.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] This can be as terse as "for condition x your derived result is y", although normally test cases describe in more detail the input scenario and what results might be expected.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] It can occasionally be a series of steps (but often steps are contained in a separate test procedure that can be exercised against multiple test cases, as a matter of economy) but with one expected result or expected outcome.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] The optional fields are a test case ID, test step, or order of execution number, related requirement(s), depth, test category, author, and check boxes for whether the test is automatable and has been automated.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] Larger test cases may also contain prerequisite states or steps, and descriptions.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] A test case should also contain a place for the actual result.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] These steps can be stored in a word processor document, spreadsheet, database, or other common repositories.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] In a database system, you may also be able to see past test results, who generated the results, and what system configuration was used to generate those results.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] These past results would usually be stored in a separate table.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] A test script is a procedure or programming code that replicates user actions.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] Initially, the term was derived from the product of work created by automated regression test tools.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] A test case will be a baseline to create test scripts using a tool or a program.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] In software development, a test suite, less commonly known as a validation suite, is a collection of test cases that are intended to be used to test a software program to show that it has some specified set of behaviors.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] A test suite often contains detailed instructions or goals for each collection of test cases and information on the system configuration to be used during testing.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] A group of test cases may also contain prerequisite states or steps and descriptions of the following tests.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] In most cases, multiple sets of values or data are used to test the same functionality of a particular feature.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] All the test values and changeable environmental components are collected in separate files and stored as test data.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] It is also useful to provide this data to the client and with the product or a project.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] There are techniques to generate Test data.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] The software, tools, samples of data input and output, and configurations are all referred to collectively as a test harness.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] A test run is a collection of test cases or test suites that the user is executing and comparing the expected with the actual results.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] Once complete, a report or all executed tests may be generated.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] Several certification programs exist to support the professional aspirations of software testers and quality assurance specialists.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] A few practitioners argue that the testing field is not ready for certification, as mentioned in the controversy section.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] is so expensive relative to its value that it should be used sparingly.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] The test automation then can be considered as a way to capture and implement the requirements.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] As a general rule, the larger the system and the greater the complexity, the greater the ROI in test automation.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] Also, the investment in tools and expertise can be amortized over multiple projects with the right level of knowledge sharing within an organization.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] Significant opposition has formed out of the ranks of the context-driven school of software testing about the ISO 29119 standard.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] Professional testing associations, such as the International Society for Software Testing, have attempted to have the standard withdrawn.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] No certification now offered actually requires the applicant to show their ability to test software.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] No certification is based on a widely accepted body of knowledge.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] Certification itself cannot measure an individual's productivity, their skill, or practical knowledge, and cannot guarantee their competence, or professionalism as a tester.
[src:traffic-mirroring/software-testing-p02] There are opposing views on the applicability of studies used to show the relative expense of fixing defects depending on their introduction and detection.
[src:traffic-mirroring/traffic-management-mirroring] This task demonstrates the traffic mirroring capabilities of Istio.
[src:traffic-mirroring/traffic-management-mirroring] Traffic mirroring, also called shadowing, is a powerful concept that allows feature teams to bring changes to production with as little risk as possible.
[src:traffic-mirroring/traffic-management-mirroring] Mirroring sends a copy of live traffic to a mirrored service.
[src:traffic-mirroring/traffic-management-mirroring] The mirrored traffic happens out of band of the critical request path for the primary service.
[src:traffic-mirroring/traffic-management-mirroring] In this task, you will first force all traffic to `v1` of a test service.
[src:traffic-mirroring/traffic-management-mirroring] Then, you will apply a rule to mirror a portion of traffic to `v2`.
[src:traffic-mirroring/traffic-management-mirroring] By default Kubernetes load balances across both versions of the `httpbin` service.
[src:traffic-mirroring/traffic-management-mirroring] In this step, you will change that behavior so that all traffic goes to `v1`.
[src:traffic-mirroring/traffic-management-mirroring] Check the logs from `httpbin-v1` and `httpbin-v2` pods.
[src:traffic-mirroring/traffic-management-mirroring] Send the traffic:Now, you should see access logging for both `v1` and `v2`.
[src:traffic-mirroring/traffic-management-mirroring] The access logs created in `v2` are the mirrored requests that are actually going to `v1`.
